debrief_1: I think the game was testing a person's ability to take risks. That is, as soon as a negative event happened, IE losing 50 points, how quickly would someone switched to another classmate, even if the current classmate gave them a bunch of positive points.
debrief_2: I tried to determine how many times a given classmate would give me a positive outcome. If, in a given round, they only gave me two or three in a row, I would then move after the second or third selection and attempt to find the classmate that was now giving positive points. I would then move back to the original if both other classmates gave me negative scores to see if the original switched back.
debrief_3: I pretty much stayed with the same strategy throughout.
feedback: I thought the survey was formatted very well and that everything ran very smoothly. The classmate game went very smooth and the feedback was almost immediate. I didn't notice any errors or mistakes throughout the study. Everything appeared to work as it should.

feedback:
I was sort of frustrated at the fact that after I finished the demographic section and listing my contacts and their relationships with each other, I was told 'You have finished the hardest part of the survey!'. And then, I am hit with what seemed like a thousand separate bubble questions about what these contacts believe about obscure conspiracies and vaccine efficacy? Really? THAT isn't the hardest part of the survey? It's not even that it was tedious or long, it's that I got what seemed like a very disingenuous message-I finished the supposed 'hardest' part of the survey in about a fifth of the time it took to do the part that came after! Also, the progress bar on top seems completely random and useless. I advanced through 75 percent of the bar visually during that supposed 'hardest' part, whereas the part that came after took up maybe 15 percent of the bar. So that to me is like understating by a factor of 25!!! how long that 'what does each person believe about alien vaccine Q-anon world trade jet fuel conspiracies' takes. 

Sorry if this sounds unhinged. I thought this was an interesting survey, really. But that message, I guess, really irked me and made me feel like I was condescended to.

debrief_1: Mental flexibility and persistence in pursuing rewards in chance situations where the outcome is uncertain but relationships are perceived to be important.
debrief_2: I started with the assumption that any of the partners could be good, then selected the one that was rewarding to work with.  If the working relationship faltered, I would try another partner until either the other partner or the prior one responded favorably, and selected that partner most consistently.  However, I also found it to be a good idea to allow that partners might realistically falter once or twice, and alternate partners may be no more reliable initially, so increasingly continued to select for the same partners through lapses, where recovery would become evident.
debrief_3: Yes, I increasingly forgave lapses in my partners performance to the extent that recovery would become evident.
